{"id":14881374,"mediaExerciseId":"86c2cfbc-6caa-4bcb-a313-c419295f1555","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"12","chapterTitle":"Some Lessons From Capital Market History","groupId":612365,"groupTitle":"Minicase Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":419,"solutions":[{"id":6249784,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will compare two different funds and decide which is better in this situation. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The Large-company stock fund, as the name suggests, refers to the investment of the pooled money of investors into the stocks of a large company. \n\nOn the other hand, the index fund refers to the mutual fund investing in a certain index which is a record of certain companies. The S&P 500 index in particular refers to top 500 publicly traded companies. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"An advantage of choosing the large-company stock fund is that it does not strictly follow the movement of any one set of companies. This means that it has the ability to outperform the market. However, it can also underperform. \n\nFor the disadvantage, the large-company stock is less diversified than the S&P 500 index fund. This is a disadvantage since a diversified portfolio is a good protection against losses since one industry can rise while the other industries fall. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"bb58dca6-21d1-4c10-928f-231db7fe6a39","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchl